  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Initial focus was primarily on hiding proceeds from illegal activities\n\n2. Significant Milestones:\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States\n- First comprehensive legal framework targeting financial crimes\n- Required financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Created international standards for combating money laundering\n- Developed recommendations for global financial regulations\n\n4. Key Legislative Developments:\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act (US)\n- Made money laundering a federal criminal offense\n- Established specific prosecution mechanisms\n\n5. Post-9/11 Expansion:\n- Patriot Act (2001) significantly expanded anti-money laundering regulations\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Increased focus on terrorist financing\n\n6. Global Progression:\n- Most developed countries implemented similar legal frameworks\n- Increased international cooperation\n- More sophisticated tracking and prosecution mechanisms\n\nThe legal history represents a progressive approach to combating financial crimes through increasingly comprehensive regulatory frameworks.",
